===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|lernen}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|leornian||to acquire knowledge}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*liznaną}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|lernen||to learn}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|learns|learning|learned|past2=learnt|past2_qual=chiefly UK}}

# To [[acquire]], or attempt to acquire [[knowledge]] or an ability to do something.
# To [[attend]] a course or other [[educational]] activity.
#* '''1719''', [[w:Daniel Defoe|Daniel Defoe]], ''[[w:Robinson Crusoe|Robinson Crusoe]]''
#*: ''For, as he took delight to introduce me, I took delight to '''learn.'''''
# To gain knowledge from a bad [[experience]] so as to [[improve]].
#: '''''learn''' from one's mistakes''
# To be [[studying]].
# To come to [[know]]; to become [[inform]]ed of; to [[find out]].
#: ''He just '''learned''' that he will be sacked.''

