===Etymology 2===
Possibly related to {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|leren}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lǣran||to teach, instruct, indoctrinate}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*laizijaną||to teach}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*laizō||lore, teaching", literally, "track, trace}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*leyəs-||to track, furrow}}. Cognate with Scots {{m|sco|lere}}, {{m|sco|leir}}, Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|leere}}, West Frisian {{m|fy|leare}}, Dutch {{m|nl|leren}}, German {{m|de|lehren}}, {{cog|sv|lära}}. See also {{l|en|lear}}, {{l|en|lore}}. But normally the Middle English word would give ''[[lere]]'', not ''learn''.

